(2, 'about', 'How it works?', '<div class=''small-12 columns''>\n	<h3>Sandbox</h3>\n	<p>The idea is simple. If you want to test something quickly, just get the new sandbox, add files and run code. You can also download your work and use in your projects.</p>\n	<p>Don''t need to clean after yourself - it will desapear if not used for more than a week (one-off) or a month (owned one). But don''t worry - by <b>used</b> we mean opened on PHPfy or as embedded sample on your website.</p>\n\n	<h3>How my code gets executed?</h3>\n	<p>Your code is placed on isolated server and accessed via http, then result of the execution is printed to the output pane.</p>\n	<p>Every execution creates it''s own environement so you cannot relay on any files created by your script (but you can send files to the script in a POST request and you can access any file created on the sandbox). We don''t block any functions so you can try...</p>\n\n</div>', 'The idea is simple. If you want to test something quickly, just get the new sandbox, add files and run code...', 'en', 1, 1),
(3, 'cookies', 'All about cookies', '<div class=''small-12 columns''>\n	<h3>General</h3>\n	<p>Yes, we use cookies (like the most of the websites). What the cookie is? <a href=''https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/HTTP_cookie'' target="_blank">Read all about it here.</a></p>\n	<p>You can disable cookies in your browser''s settings. However there is no guarantee that the service will still work as expected.</p>\n\n	<h3>What cookies do we store?</h3>\n	<p>PHPfy stores session cookie and cookie policy acceptance cookie (to not to show you annoying cookie popup everytime you open this website)</p>\n	<p>Some other cookies comming from external services may be stored. Please check their cookie policy as well.</p>\n	<p>External service providers: </p>\n	<ul>\n		<li>Google - OAuth, tracking and analitics</li>\n		<li>Facebook - OAuth</li>\n		<li>LinkedIn - OAuth</li>\n		<li>GitHub - OAuth</li>\n	</ul>\n\n	<h3>Can I disable cookies?</h3>\n	<p>Yes. But expect some difficulties when using the service.</p>\n</div>', 'Yes, we use cookies (like the most of the websites). Find all the details here...', 'en', 1, 1),
(4, 'tnc', 'Terms & Conditions', '<div class=''small-12 medium-6 columns''>\n	<h3>Basics</h3>\n	<ul>\n		<li>PHPfy is a free service</li>\n		<li>Cannot guarantee that it will be up 100% of time</li>\n		<li>It''s a beta version so some of the functionality may not work as expected</li>\n	</ul>\n\n	<h3>Privacy</h3>\n	<ul>\n		<li>All the personal data is stored in secure database</li>\n		<li>We won''t send you a SPAM or marketing emails</li>\n		<li>All the PHPfy content belongs to PHPfy</li>\n		<li>Sandbox and it''s content belongs to it''s owner</li>\n	</ul>\n\n	<h3>User account</h3>\n	<ul>\n		<li>It''s owned and managed by user</li>\n		<li>Can be deleted at any time by the user</li>\n		<li>Deleting account created trought social media websites (like Facebook) will not affect original account</li>\n</div>\n<div class=''small-12 medium-6 columns''>\n	<h3>Sandboxes</h3>\n	<ul>\n		<li>Sandbox is managed by its owner</li>\n		<li>One-off sandbox (the one without the owner) will be deleted if not used for more than one week</li>\n		<li>Sandbox owned by the PHPfy user will be deleted if not used for more than one month</li>\n		<li>Sandbox is considered used if it was open by anyone or viewed as code embedded on the external website</li>\n	</ul>\n\n	<h3>Legal stuff</h3>\n	<ul>\n		<li>The service is provided "AS IS", without warranty of any kind, express or implied, including but not limited to the warranties of fitness for a particular purpose and noninfringement. In no event shall the the authors or copyright holders be liable for any claim, damages or other liability, whether in an action of contract, tort or otherwise, arising from, out of or in connection with the service or the use or other dealings in the service.</li>\n		<li>Sandbox may be deleted if its content is illegal, in some way harmful or it may cause any damage to the service.</li>\n		<li>User''s account may be blocked or deleted as a result of unacceptable bechaviour</li>\n	</ul>\n</div>', 'Small print made clear :)', 'en', 1, 1),
(5, 'languages', 'Supported Languages', '<div class=''small-12 columns''>\r\n	<h3>Server side</h3>\r\n\r\n	<div class=''row''>\r\n\r\n		<div class="small-12 medium-4 columns">\r\n		    <div class=''infoicons''>\r\n		        <i class=''devicon-php-plain''></i>\r\n		    </div>\r\n		    <p>There are several versions of PHP available and you can pick the one you want to use from <b>run options</b> menu.</p>\r\n		    <p>You can use any function available in the PHP version of choice and most of the popular extensions. For the full list of extensions just execute <i>phpinfo();</i>.</p>\r\n		    <p>You won''t be able to use <b>Apache</b> specific functions (as it''s not Apache server).</p>\r\n		    <p>Use <i>include</i> or <i>require</i> to include other scripts from the sandbox. You can read any file existing in the sandbox or upload files using html form (just put the name of your php script in <i>action</i> attribute). None of the saved files will be available to read next time you execute script</p>\r\n		</div>\r\n\r\n		<div class="small-12 medium-4 columns">\r\n		    <div class=''infoicons''>\r\n		        <i class=''devicon-python-plain''></i>\r\n		    </div>\r\n		    <p>You can use python scripts executed via http request (as CGI module). Just make sure that the first thing you print is http header.</p>\r\n		    <p>Use <i>import</i> to include python scripts from the sandbox (you don''t need to create <i>__init__.py</i> - just use the file name).</p>\r\n		    <p>Make request from html page using any type of http request (that includes posting files).</p>\r\n		</div>\r\n\r\n		<div class="small-12 medium-4 columns">\r\n		    <div class=''infoicons''>\r\n		        <img src=''/modules/main/img/perl.png'' class=''icon''>\r\n		    </div>\r\n		    <p>Create perl scripts and packages. Just use your package file name with <i>use</i> or perl script name with <i>required</i>.</p>\r\n		    <p>Perl scripts are executed via http (using CGI) and the first printed line should be a valid http header.</p>\r\n		    <p>Check the list of modules you can use <a href=''/cms/perlmodules'' class=''mixedlink'' data-target=''cmsContent''>here</a></p>\r\n		</div>\r\n	</div>\r\n\r\n	<h3>Client side</h3>\r\n\r\n	<div class=''row''>\r\n		<div class="small-12 medium-4 columns">\r\n		    <div class=''infoicons''>\r\n		        <i class=''devicon-html5-plain''></i>\r\n		    </div>\r\n		    <p>Create html page to test your JS or ajax request to the backend (php, python, perl). If you won''t add html tag, doctype and headers this will be auto generated based on the <b>run options</b>. </p>\r\n		    <p>You can link any file on the sandbox or use it as a form action target. You can attach css or js files created on your sandbox as well.</p>\r\n		</div>\r\n		<div class="small-12 medium-4 columns">\r\n		    <div class=''infoicons''>\r\n		        <i class=''devicon-javascript-plain''></i>\r\n		    </div>\r\n		    <p>You can execute javascript files directly and they will be wrapped in html. You can specify additional options from the run menu.</p>\r\n		</div>\r\n		<div class="small-12 medium-4 columns">\r\n		    <div class=''infoicons''>\r\n		        <i class=''devicon-css3-plain''></i>\r\n		    </div>\r\n		    <p>create css files to use them on html pages on your sandbox. You won''t be able to execute the css file on its own but it''s just a few clicks to create test html page as well.</p>\r\n		</div>\r\n	</div>\r\n\r\n	<h3>Data source</h3>\r\n\r\n	<div class=''row''>\r\n		<div class="small-12 columns">\r\n		<p>Add <b>xml</b>, <b>json</b>, <b>csv</b> or <b>txt</b> files to pass additional data to the scripts you''re testing. You can access them by the file name both on the server and client side</p>\r\n		</div>\r\n	</div>\r\n\r\n</div>', 'What you can use on PHPfy', 'en', 1, 2),
